	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Ethiopian coffee sector caught by falling global prices</h1>

			
			<h4>
												22 July 2013
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>Ethiopia is Africa’s largest coffee producer and the fifth largest producer in the world, producing mainly arabica coffee. Production takes place primarily on smallholder farms (95%), under traditional production and farm management systems. These range from wild and semi-wild collection to managed smallholder farming operations. Production, according to a recent report by the USDA, is “characterized by limited use of fertilizers and pesticides with manual cultivation and drying processes”. Production per hectare is very low, with no specialised government institution providing extension support for coffee production.</p><p>While traders claim that Ethiopian coffee is organically produced, it is not officially certified as such by internationally recognised bodies. Nevertheless, Ethiopian coffee is “in high demand in the international markets, and it is specifically valued for its special aroma and distinct flavor”.</p><p>USDA notes that Ethiopia is one of the largest consumers of coffee in Africa, with nearly half of its production being consumed nationally. Prices of coffee are usually higher on the local market, with the government banning sales of export-grade coffee on the local market. &nbsp;</p><p>According to USDA, nearly all coffee is sold on the government-established Ethiopia Commodity Exchange (ECX), either directly through coffee producers’ cooperatives or intermediaries. The ECX is “a public market facilitating institution”, and was set up mainly “to eliminate the huge number of middlemen involved in coffee distribution and to enable coffee farmers to benefit from prevailing market prices”. However, USDA has noted that “coffee sold through ECX is considered as commodity coffee and will not get the possible premiums of being organic coffee.” Ethiopia mainly exports “green beans with only a very small amount of roasted beans”.</p><p>The USDA report notes that the coffee sector generates around 25% of Ethiopia’s export earnings: trade in coffee is regulated with the aim of maximising foreign exchange. All coffee-sector-related enterprises require special licences to operate, and a government regulation introduced in May 2011 limits the amount of stock an exporter can store without having a shipment contract.</p><p><b>Ethiopian coffee production for marketing years 2011/12 to 2013/14 (60-kg bags)</b></p><table class="renderedtable" border="1" cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0" width="590">
<tr>
<td width="146" valign="top">  &nbsp;
  </td><td width="148" valign="top">  MY 2011/12
  </td><td width="148" valign="top">  MY 2012/13
  </td><td width="148" valign="top">  MY 2013/14
  </td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td width="146" valign="top">  Arabica
  </td><td width="148" valign="top">  6,320,000
  </td><td width="148" valign="top">  6,325,000
